    <name>
				<text>16.5.2.6 Product of Maclaurin series</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">

    <li>
        <p>If \(\cos x=1-\dfrac{x^2}{2!}+\dfrac{x^4}{4!}+\cdots\) then find the Maclaurin expansion of <span class="math inline">\(\cos^2x\)</span> up to powers of <span class="math inline">\(x^4\)</span></p>
        <p>\(\cos^2x =1-\) [[input:ans1]] \(x^2+\) [[input:ans2]] \(x^4-\) [[input:ans3]] \(x^6-\cdots\) [[validation:ans1]][[validation:ans2]][[validation:ans3]]</p>
        <p> [[feedback:prt1]] [[feedback:prt2]] [[feedback:prt3]]</p>
    </li>

    <li>
        <p>Hence write down the expansion of <span class="math inline">\(\sin^2x\)</span> to powers of <span class="math inline">\(x^6\)</span>. (<em>Hint: \(\sin^2x=1-\cos^2x\)</em>)</p>
      <p> \(\sin^2x=\) [[input:ans4]][[validation:ans4]] \(+\cdots\) [[feedback:prt4]]</p>
    </li>

</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>
<p>First, write down the expansion of cosine: <span class="math inline">\(\cos x=1-\dfrac{x^2}{2!}+\dfrac{x^4}{4!}+\cdots\)</span></p>
<p>Now, by multiplication, find the expansion of <span class="math inline">\(\cos^2x\)</span>:</p>
<p><span class="math inline">\(\cos^2 x=\left(1-\dfrac{x^2}{2!}+\dfrac{x^4}{4!}\cdots\right)
\left(1-\dfrac{x^2}{2!}+\dfrac{x^4}{4!}\cdots\right)\)</span> <span class="math inline">\(\quad\qquad =(1-\dfrac{x^2}{2!}+\dfrac{x^4}{4!}\cdots )
+(-\dfrac{x^2}{2!}+\dfrac{x^4}{4}\cdots )+
(\dfrac{x^4}{4!}\cdots )+\cdots =1-x^2+\dfrac{x^4}{3}-\dfrac{2x^6}{45}\cdots\)</span></p>
  </li>
  <li>
<p>Now obtain the expansion of <span class="math inline">\(\sin^2x\)</span> using a suitable trigonometric identity: <span class="math inline">\(\sin^2x=1-\cos^2x=1-\left(1-x^2+\dfrac{x^4}{3}-\dfrac{2x^6}{45}+\cdots\right)=
x^2-\dfrac{x^4}{3}+\dfrac{2x^6}{45}+\cdots\)</span></p>
  </li>
<p>As an alternative approach you could obtain the power series expansion for <span class="math inline">\(\cos^2x\)</span> by using the trigonometric identity <span class="math inline">\(\cos^2x\equiv\dfrac{1}{2}(1+\cos 2x)\)</span>.</p></ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
